<tr><td>Cereus peruvianus, the Peruvian apple cactus, has edible fruit when full size (up to
10&nbsp;m tall). This is the monstrose form, which instead of growing from a single areole per
branch, grows from random points to produce a plant that's asymmetrical and covered in knobby
bumps. Hopefully it won't grow as tall as normal form.
<td width=10><td width=75>
<span class="thumbnail"><img src="images/s01.jpg" width=75 height=75 border=0 alt=""><span>
