<tr><td>Hylocereus undatus is a climbing shade-tolerant soft-stemmed cactus that probably
originated from the Caribbean. Hybrids and selections are now grown around
the tropical world for fruit: pitaya or dragon fruit. Unopened flowers are also eaten as a
vegetable. Most plants have 3-sided stems, but this one is 4-sided; 5-sided also exist.
<td width=10><td width=75>
<span class="thumbnail"><img src="images/s84.jpg" width=75 height=75 border=0 alt=""><span>
<img src="images/s84.jpg" width=800 height=518 alt="Hylocereus undatus"></span></span>
<tr><td>Kalanchoe daigremontiana from Madagascar only reproduces vegetatively from
plantlets that develop on its leaf margins. Although it does bloom, no male plants have ever been
found. It's nicknamed 'mother of thousands' for good reason. A too-easy succulent to grow and
multiply.
<td width=10><td width=75>
<span class="thumbnail"><img src="images/s15.jpg" width=75 height=75 border=0 alt=""><span>
<img src="images/s15.jpg" width=800 height=616 alt="Kalanchoe daigremontiana"></span></span>
<tr><td>Kalanchoe hybrids based on K.bossfeldiana are widely sold. All parts of all Kalanchoe
contain cardiotoxic bufadienolides to deter herbivores, so should be kept away from
small children and pets.
<td width=10><td width=75>
<span class="thumbnail"><img src="images/s32.jpg" width=75 height=75 border=0 alt=""><span>
<img src="images/s32.jpg" width=800 height=757 alt="Kalanchoe hybrid"></span></span>
<tr><td>Kalanchoe beharensis has velvety leaves and is from Madagascar.
